it's important respect eachother, but also acknowledge that we have a lot of work to do. but these are just the thoughts of some 18 year old and there are also lots of perspectives to consider!

these corps are homes and families, and many people do drum corps because of the wonderful and life changing experiences it presents, AND there are still people in this activity who shouldn't be allowed near kids and there are lots of problems to fix.
i've seen drastic differences in this activity from coming from a folded corps who was (and still is) the laughing stock of dci to being a member of the bluecoats.
our positive experiences can coexist with other people's negative ones, and they do not have to cancel each other out, but it's important to acknowledge when people have been mistreated.

we all love our corps, and it's important to be sensitive and understanding when making comments about other people's homes, but i also think if you truly love your corps you should hold it accountable.

i don't think theres anything wrong with acknowledging problems in the DCI community and giving victims of mistreatment a platform to be viewed. however, it's easy to become defensive in this process.
